  "prompt": "Is money laundering a crime?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a crime. It involves disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions, to make the money appear to be from a legitimate source. The process usually consists of three stages:\n\n1. **Placement**: Introducing the illicit funds into the financial system.\n2. **Layering**: Conducting a series of transactions to obscure the source of the funds.\n3. **Integration**: Merging the \"cleaned\" money back into the economy as legitimate funds.\n\nMoney laundering is illegal because it allows criminals to profit from illegal activities and can undermine the integrity of financial systems. Laws and regulations to combat money laundering are in place in most countries, and international cooperation often occurs to tackle this issue, given its global nature. Penalties for money laundering can include heavy fines, forfeiture of assets, and imprisonment.",
